FIND(1)                          User Commands                         FIND(1)

NAME
       find - search for files in a directory hierarchy

SYNOPSIS
       find [path...] [expression]

DESCRIPTION
       Search for files in a directory hierarchy.  For each file found,
       evaluate the given expression.

       If no path is specified, the current directory (.) is used.
       If no action is specified, -print is implied.

   GLOBAL OPTIONS
       -maxdepth LEVELS
              descend at most LEVELS levels below the starting points

       -mindepth LEVELS
              do not apply any tests at levels less than LEVELS

       -depth process each directory's contents before the directory

       -xdev, -mount
              don't descend directories on other filesystems

       -help, --help
              display this help

       -version, --version
              display version

   TESTS
       -name PATTERN
              base of file name matches shell pattern PATTERN

       -iname PATTERN
              like -name, but the match is case insensitive

       -path PATTERN, -wholename PATTERN
              file name matches shell pattern PATTERN

       -ipath PATTERN, -iwholename PATTERN
              like -path, but the match is case insensitive

       -type [bcdpfls]
              file is of type: block, char, directory, pipe, regular
              file, symbolic link, or socket

       -size N[bcwkMG]
              file uses N units of space (b=512, c=bytes, w=2-byte
              words, k=kibibytes, M=mebibytes, G=gibibytes)

       -empty file is empty (zero size or empty directory)

       -perm [-/]MODE
              file's permission bits are exactly MODE (octal).
              With -, all bits in MODE must be set.
              With /, any bit in MODE must be set.

       -newer FILE
              file was modified more recently than FILE

       -mtime N
              file's data was last modified N*24 hours ago

       -atime N
              file was last accessed N*24 hours ago

       -ctime N
              file's status was last changed N*24 hours ago

       -mmin N
              file's data was last modified N minutes ago

       -amin N
              file was last accessed N minutes ago

       -cmin N
              file's status was last changed N minutes ago

       -links N
              file has N hard links

       -readable
              readable by current user

       -writable
              writable by current user

       -executable
              executable by current user

       -true  always true

       -false always false

       Numeric arguments accept +N (greater than), -N (less than), or
       N (exactly).

   ACTIONS
       -print print the full file name, followed by a newline

       -print0
              print the full file name, followed by a NUL character

       -printf FORMAT
              print format string.  Directives:
              %p  file's name
              %f  file's basename
              %h  file's dirname
              %s  file's size in bytes
              %k  file's size in 1K blocks
              %m  file's permission bits (octal)
              %M  file's permissions (symbolic)
              %u  file's user ID
              %g  file's group ID
              %n  number of hard links
              %T@ modification time as seconds.nanoseconds
              %A@ access time as seconds.nanoseconds
              %C@ change time as seconds.nanoseconds
              %y  file's type (single letter)
              %d  file's depth in the directory tree
              %%  a literal percent sign

       -exec command {} ;
              execute command; {} is replaced by the current file name

       -exec command {} +
              like -exec but multiple file names are passed at once

       -execdir command {} ;
              like -exec, but command is run from the directory
              containing the matched file

       -delete
              delete files (implies -depth)

       -ls    list current file in ls -dils format

       -prune if the file is a directory, do not descend into it

       -quit  exit immediately

   OPERATORS
       ! expr, -not expr
              true if expr is false

       expr1 -a expr2, expr1 -and expr2
              AND; expr2 is not evaluated if expr1 is false

       expr1 -o expr2, expr1 -or expr2
              OR; expr2 is not evaluated if expr1 is true

       ( expr )
              force precedence

       Implicit AND between adjacent tests.

